<h3>Where to Start</h3>
<p>Create dedicated pages for each tattoo style you offer:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>/styles/traditional-tattoo</code>. Target "traditional tattoo artist [city]"</li>
<li><code>/styles/realism-tattoo</code>. Target "realistic tattoo artist [city]"</li>
<li><code>/styles/fine-line-tattoo</code>. Target "fine line tattoo artist [city]"</li>
<li><code>/styles/japanese-tattoo</code>. Target "Japanese tattoo artist [city]"</li>
<li><code>/styles/blackwork-tattoo</code>. Target "blackwork tattoo artist [city]"</li>
</ul>
<p>Each page includes example work, a description of the style, pricing guidance, and a booking link. These pages rank for long-tail keywords that generic portfolio pages never capture.</p>
<h3>Artist Profile Pages</h3>
<p>Create a dedicated page for each tattoo artist at your shop. Include their name, specialties, years of experience, a curated portfolio, and a direct booking link. Artist profile pages target "[artist name] tattoo" searches and capture clients who research specific artists before booking.</p>
<p>Artist pages also help with Google's E-E-A-T signals. Named artists with verifiable portfolios and bios signal real expertise to Google. An anonymous shop with no artist information looks less trustworthy than one that showcases its team.</p>
<h3>Local Landing Pages</h3>
<p>If your shop serves clients from multiple cities, create dedicated landing pages for each city. "Tattoo Shop in Round Rock TX" and "Tattoo Shop in Georgetown TX" target different local searches. Each page needs unique content about serving that area. Do not duplicate the same text with only the city name swapped.</p>
<p>For keyword research methods, see our guide on <a href="/blog/build-topical-authority/">building topical authority</a>.</p>
<h2>Portfolio Image SEO for Tattoo Shops</h2>
<p>Tattoo shops live and die by visual content. Your portfolio is your biggest selling tool. But most tattoo websites have zero image SEO. Images named "IMG_4872.jpg" with no alt text. Google cannot index what it cannot read.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" alt="Tattoo portfolio image SEO checklist" src="/images/blog/tattoo-seo-image-checklist.webp" /></p>
<h3>The Tattoo Image SEO Checklist</h3>
<ul>
<li>[ ] <strong>Rename every file descriptively.</strong> "black-grey-portrait-tattoo-forearm-austin.jpg" ranks in Google Images. "IMG_4872.jpg" does not.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Write alt text with keywords.</strong> "Black and grey portrait tattoo on forearm by [Artist Name] at [Shop Name], Austin TX." This describes the image for Google and screen readers.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Compress images to under 200KB.</strong> Use WebP format. Tools: ShortPixel, TinyPNG, or Squoosh. Large uncompressed images kill page speed.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Use lazy loading.</strong> Only load images as the visitor scrolls down. Keeps initial page load fast.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Add structured data.</strong> ImageObject schema with description, creator, and location properties.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Organize by style and artist.</strong> Separate gallery pages by tattoo style and by artist. Each page becomes a ranking target.</li>
</ul>
<p>For a deeper guide, see our post on <a href="/blog/blog-image-optimization-seo/">blog image optimization for SEO</a>.</p>
<h3>Why Image SEO Matters for Tattoo Shops</h3>
<p>People search Google Images for tattoo inspiration. "Forearm tattoo ideas," "sleeve tattoo designs," and "small tattoo ideas" generate millions of searches per month. If your portfolio images appear in those results with proper alt text and filenames, they drive traffic to your site without any additional effort.</p>
