<h2>Reviews and Reputation for Tattoo Shops</h2>
<p>Getting tattooed is a trust decision. Clients put permanent art on their body. They research heavily before booking. <a href="https://www.brightlocal.com/resources/local-seo-statistics/">68% of consumers only use businesses rated 4+ stars</a>. For tattoo shops, that threshold is even higher. Most clients want 4.5+ stars before they trust an artist with their skin.</p>
<h3>How to Build Reviews Consistently</h3>
<p>62% of tattoo inquiries happen outside business hours, between 7 and 9 PM. That means your best review request window is immediately after the appointment, when the client is excited about their new piece.</p>
<p><strong>The tattoo shop review system:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li><strong>At checkout:</strong> "We would love a Google review if you have a minute. Here is the link." (Hand them a card with a QR code)</li>
<li><strong>Same-day text:</strong> Send an automated follow-up text 2 hours after the appointment with a direct Google review link</li>
<li><strong>Aftercare email (day 3):</strong> Send aftercare instructions with a gentle review reminder at the bottom</li>
<li><strong>Social media moment:</strong> When the client posts their tattoo and tags your shop, reply with a thank-you and a review request</li>
</ol>
<p>For the complete review playbook, see our guide on <a href="/blog/get-more-google-reviews-local-business/">getting more Google reviews</a>.</p>
<h3>Responding to Reviews</h3>
<p>Respond to every review within 24 to 48 hours. Thank positive reviewers by name and mention their tattoo style or the artist who did the work. For negative reviews, acknowledge the concern, avoid being defensive, and take it offline. See our guide on <a href="/blog/respond-to-negative-google-reviews/">responding to negative reviews</a>.</p>
